TY STRUCTURES BEYOND THE STATE -- t13. The End of Closet Political Transnationalism? The Role of Homeland Politics in the Political Incorporation of Turks and Kurds in Europe -- t14. Organizing Immigration Interests in the European Union: Constraints and Opportunities for Supranational Migration Regulation and Integration -- tPART VI. IMMIGRANTS' POLITICAL RESOURCES AND STRATEGIES -- t15. The State and Ethno-Religious Mobilization in Britain -- t16. Differences in the City: Parallel Worlds, Migration, and Inclusion of Differences in the Urban Space -- t17. In Pursuit of Inclusion: Citizenship Acquisition among Asian Immigrants -- t18. Entering the Precincts of Power: Do National Differences Matter for Immigrant Minority Political Representation? -- tPART VII. THE ROAD AHEAD -- t19. Understanding Immigrant Political Incorporation through Comparison -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributor Biographies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor immigrants, politics can play a significant role in determining whether and how they assimilate. In Bringing Outsiders In, leading social scientists present individual cases and work toward a comparative synthesis of how immigrants affect—and are affected by—civic life on both sides of the Atlantic.Just as in the United States, large immigrant minority communities have been emerging across Europe. While these communities usually make up less than one-tenth of national populations, they typically have a large presence in urban areas, sometimes approaching a majority. That immigrants can have an even greater political salience than their population might suggest has been demonstrated in recent years in places as diverse as Sweden and France. Attending to how local and national states encourage or discourage political participation, the authors assess the relative involvement of immigrants in a wide range of settings. Jennifer Hochschild and John Mollenkopf provide a context for the particular cases and comparisons and draw a set of analytic and empirical conclusions regarding incorporation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzEurope, WesternvCongresses. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzNorth AmericavCongresses. 0aPolitical participationzEurope, WesternvCongresses. 0aPolitical participationzNorth AmericavCongresses. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAlba, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCattacin, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuyvendak, Jan Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Amato, Gianni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoner, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraga, Luis Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHochschild, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHochschild, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJoppke, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahav, Gallya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartiniello, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinkenberg, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinnite, Lorraine C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aModood, Tariq, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMollenkopf, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov